 to do so. He also engages the political and moral issues raised by the idea of a multicultural art history. Focusing on a consideration of intersecting artistic traditions, Carrier negotiates the way meaning and understanding shift or are altered when a visual object from one culture, for example, is inserted into the visual tradition of another culture. A World Art History and Its Objects proposes the use of temporal narrative as a way to begin to understand a multicultural art history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aART / Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271036069zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271036069423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271036069.jpg  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_AD  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_AD  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK